I think the topic of memory has a lot of room for philosophical
discussion. In fact, I really think it needs more. My understanding of
the word &#39;inteligence&#39; is tied to an ability to make decisions. A lemur
that selects a series of pictures in historical order is interesting in
more ways than a display of memory. It was intelligent enough to decide
to select the pictures in some particular order, which it happened to be
able to remember. I&#39;m more interested in why the lemur decided to select
the pictures in order. Can we evolve an ANN that could make that
decision? Normally a programmer assumes &#39;of course we can&#39; and we code
it to make sure that happens. If we do that, are we developing something
intelligent, or putting our intelligence into a program, like a
conventional decision making method? 


Yes, that&#39;s exaclty my line of thought. I have been 
pushing this notion for about six months now. You 
might like to look at my 4Play project, on my website. 
It uses neuroevolution (but not NEAT) to evolve an 
ANN that makes active use of short term memory. Also, 
if you look in the archive at yahoo groups for this 
group you can find several posts by me about the 
general subject of short term memory. 

I hope you make a NEAT ANN that can remember stuff and 
repeat it back. 

